<br>
I have nothing against nudity in art. I just find it a fine line to walk when trying to moderate it. You always get immature guys that want to draw bent over chicks and pole dancer stuff and they claim it as &quot;art&quot; but if someone posts a guy bent over or messing with his &quot;junk&quot;, then they are the first to run screaming out of the room. I have to keep the board an even playing field for all sexes so I try to have nudity limited to partial and non-erotic. <br>
<br>
it can be sexy...but not overtly sexual. See what I mean? fine lines. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uanyte.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Anyte</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(12/18/01 10:03:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1198.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://liquid2k.com/anyte/photos/bsnap7.jpg width=120 length=102></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Is it really?</span><hr size=1> I know what you mean.  I don't like some of the images I see posted, but I would never ask for the current policy to change.  If I happen across one a drawing I'm not too fond of I either leave it alone or give an honest crit on the work.  I have also started keeping track of who is doing those types of drawings and I just make a point of not looking at their drawings unless the title indicates that it might be something other than nude art.<br>
